        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Marius filius, cum Gn[aeus] Carbone per vim Consul; vna significatione literaru[m] Damasippum Pra[e]torem satellitem suum iussit, 
                        quicquid erat in vrbe patritiorum interficere: bonusq[ue] satelles iussa domini diligenter est exsecutus. Nam specie consulendi 
                        contracto Senatu, omnes patritios interemit. Hodiè facinus horribile diceretur. 
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Gaius Marius the Younger"/>
                <person name="Gnaeus Papirius Carbo"/> 
                <person name="Damasippus"/> 
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Marius junior, consul by force together with Gnaeus Carbo, ordered his henchman, the praetor Damasippus, with a single hint in a letter to kill
                whoever of the patricians was in town. Being a good henchman, he carefully carried out the commands of his master. For after the senate had 
                been brought together on the pretext of consultation, he killed all patricians. Today this would be called a dreadful crime. 
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        De bello ciuili, Mariano atq[ue] Syllano. Augustinus l. 3. c. 27. de Ciu. Qualis fuerit Syllana victoria, vindex Mariana[e] crudelitatis.
                        c. 28. De Syllanis actibus, quorum se da[e]mones ostentauerunt adiutores. l. 1. [sic] c. 24. De connexione bellorum, qua[e] aduentum 
                        Christi plurima, et grauissima pra[e]cesserunt, L. 3. c. 30. pra[e]sertim bella Marij, et Sylla[e]; Sertorij, et Catilina[e]; Lepidi, 
                        et Catuli; Pompeij, et Ca[e]saris; Augusti, et inimicoru[m], Cassij, Bruti, Sexti Pompeij, L. Antonij, qui Triumuiri frater, Lepidi 
                        triumuiri, M. ipsius Antonij Triumuiri. Quo victo, omnibus iam confectis bellis ciuilibus, solus superfuit Imperator. 
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Gaius Marius"/>
                <person name="Sulla"/>
                <person name="Augustine"/>
                <person name="Quintus Sertorius"/>
                <person name="Lucius Sergius Catilina"/> 
                <person name="Marcus Aemilius Lepidus"/>
                <person name="Gaius Lutatius Catulus"/>
                <person name="Pompey"/>
                <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                <person name="Augustus"/>
                <person name="Gaius Cassius Longinus"/>
                <person name="Marcus Junius Brutus the Younger"/>
                <person name="Sextus Pompey"/>
                <person name="Lucius Antonius"/> 
                <person name="Mark Antony"/>
                <book title="De Civitate Dei"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Of the Civil War of Marius and Sulla: Augustine, bk. 3, ch. 27 of the City of God; Of the nature of Sulla’s victory, which avenged the cruelty
                of Marius, ch. 28; The deeds of Sulla, of which the demons showed themselves to be the helpers, bk. 1 [=2!], ch. 24; Of the numerous and most 
                grave series of wars which preceded the advent of Christ, bk 3, ch. 30; especially the wars of Marius and Sulla, Sertorius and Catiline; 
                Lepidus and Catulus; Pompey and Caesar; Augustus and his enemies Cassius, Brutus, Sextus Pompey, Lucius Antonius, who was the brother of the 
                triumvir; the triumvir Lepidus, and the triumvir Marcus Antonius himself. After he was defeated, with all others already killed in the civil 
                wars, he was left as the only commander. 
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
